<h2>Solar Panels in Virginia</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Virginia's solar resource potential is substantial, with the state receiving between 4.2 to 5.0 peak sun hours daily depending on location. Northern Virginia areas like Arlington and Fairfax typically see slightly lower solar irradiance due to latitude and occasional weather patterns, while southern regions including Virginia Beach and Norfolk enjoy higher solar production potential. The state's relatively stable weather patterns, with approximately 200 sunny days annually, provide consistent solar energy generation throughout the year.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Virginia can produce between 1,100 to 1,400 kilowatt-hours per installed kilowatt annually. This means a 6kW system, suitable for an average Virginia home, can generate approximately 7,200 to 8,400 kWh per year, covering 60-80% of a typical household's electricity consumption. Seasonal variations show peak production during late spring and early summer months, with December and January showing the lowest production levels at approximately 60% of peak summer generation.</p>

<p>The optimal solar panel orientation in Virginia is south-facing with a tilt angle between 35-40 degrees, matching the state's latitude. However, east and west-facing installations can still achieve 80-90% of optimal production, making solar viable for homes with various roof orientations. Advanced monitoring systems and microinverters help maximize production even when shading or roof complexity presents challenges.</p>

